Description: Bruegel. Death of Virgin. There seems to be some connection with Dirck Crabeth's window of the Death of the Virgin in Oude Kerk, A[mster]dam. Drawing in Rijkprentenkabinet see [Otto Benesch, Zu van Regteren - Altenas van Gheyns Monographie], [Die] Graphische Künste, 1937, II/4, p. 144 [143-146] & [I.Q. van] Regteren Altena, [= Teekeningen van Dirck Crabeth] in Oud Holland, LV, 1938, p. 107-114 - What is the date of Crabeth's design? There are only the 12 apostles around the bed (a 4 poster with curtains) but St. Peter supporting the candle, halo by Mary (who is lying back already dead?) the theory of the grisailles - the silhouette of the standing apostle at the foot of the bed have something in common with Bruegel's composition. The bed is parallel to the picture plane and three are in effects of light & dark - although then the same clouds at the top of the composition.
